ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Borrowing Mod.TG's comment from a prior ProMED-mail posting, "Many species
of cyanobacteria produce populations that are toxic to humans and animals.
Blue-green pond scums have been linked to the poisoning of cattle and dogs,
and occasionally people. Some species of cyanobacteria appear to be
nontoxic and are harvested as a food source. It is therefore not
recommended that wild algae populations be gathered and eaten without some
knowledge of the organisms involved. _Anabaena_ is a blue-green alga." -
Mod.MPP]
